<rss version="2.0"><channel><title>守护者</title><description>卫报全文RSS。获取更多全文RSS：https://feedx.net</description><link/> https://theguardian.com <item><title><![CDATA[‘A titan of the climate movement’: tributes pour in for Saleemul Huq]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2023/nov/01/a-titan-of-the-climate-movement-tributes-pour-in-for-saleemul-huq]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-11-01T10:00:07Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/2a906dbbc5b46bb33b85c4fecc115ab60e8b9ce6/0_394_5830_3500 /master/5830.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=10116623352ee1191330d26eba8b84ba&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;Saleemul Huq 教授，摄于苏格兰格拉斯哥第 26 届缔约方大会。&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;悼念之情纷至沓来著名的孟加拉国科学家 Saleemul Huq 教授于 10 月 28 日去世，他的足迹遍及全世界。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Huq 现年 71 岁，是一位广受赞誉的学者、坚持不懈的气候活动家和国际气候变化中心主任。孟加拉国的研究和能力建设组织发展组织（ICCCAD）。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;孟加拉国环境、森林和气候变化部部长沙哈布·乌丁表示，胡克的去世对国家和其他国家来说是无法挽回的损失世界的。周日下午，数百人聚集在达卡的高尔杉协会清真寺表达最后的敬意，周日在阿布扎比举行的 G77 峰会前，人们为他默哀一分钟。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;乌干达气候活动家凡妮莎·纳凯特 (Vanessa Nakate) 告诉《卫报》，多年来她有幸与胡克多次合作。 “除了为最弱势群体而奋斗之外，胡克还非常慷慨地投入了自己的时间，”她说。 “我记得在第 26 届缔约方会议上，我有机会就损失和损害接受大型媒体采访，但希望有一位专家与我一起发言。他立即回应了我的请求，放下手中的事情，穿过格拉斯哥会议中心来和我会合。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Mohamed Adow，能源与气候智囊机构 Power Shift Africa 主任，&lt;a href=&quot; https://twitter.com/PowerShftAfrica/status/1719343530823319978&quot;>;在 X（以前的 Twitter）上将 Huq 描述为“气候运动的巨人，在欧洲和北美科学家主导的领域中脱颖而出。很高兴看到孟加拉国人在全球舞台上以如此权威和洞察力发表演讲。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;克里斯蒂安娜·菲格雷斯，哥斯达黎加气候领导人、&lt;a href=&quot;http:// /unfccc.int/&quot;>;联合国气候变化框架公约&lt;/a>;（UNFCCC）表示，Huq 是一位“&lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/CFigueres/status/1718949300481257886&quot;>;顽强、有远见的人&lt;/a>;。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Huq 是基于社区的适应的早期力量——这是孟加拉国农村地区一个行之有效的概念——其重点是帮助社区找到自己的气候危机解决方案，例如改善防洪能力并根据天气变化调整种植模式。他坚信，受影响的社区需要“占据主导地位”，到 20 世纪 90 年代，他积极参与国际气候谈判，帮助气候脆弱国家将其个人需求列入备受瞩目的联合国谈判议程。&lt;/p >; &lt;p>;在 Huq 的众多成就中，Huq 是&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.unep.org/news-and-stories/story/what-you-need-know -about-cop27-loss-and-damage-fund&quot;>;​​损失和损害基金&lt;/a>;，富裕国家（迄今为止为此付出了最大努力）通过该基金支付费用，帮助发展中国家应对全球变暖的后果。尽管这个想法在 2015 年《巴黎气候协议》之前获得了关注，但直到 2022 年才签署了协议。 “损失和损坏不是援助，”胡克说。 “当金钱作为援助提供时，所有权力都掌握在捐助者手中。这是一种不平等的关系。”&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;4a3064faa96255b92e6a32567a45a0a3c101facf&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/4a3064faa96255b92e6a32567a45a0a3c101facf/0_0_5519 _3105/1000.jpg&quot; alt= “‘对他的时间非常慷慨’……Huq 在 Cop26 上。” width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;563&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;“对他的时间非常慷慨”……Huq 在 Cop26。&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;照片：由 IISD 提供&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt; /figure>; &lt;p>;Huq 于 2022 年荣获 OBE，曾任孟加拉国独立大学教授；国际环境与发展研究所高级研究员；以及 Cop28 咨询委员会的成员。他是一位多产的作家和研究人员，是&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.ipcc.ch/&quot;>;IPCC&lt;/a>;第三次、第四次和第五次全球气候评估的主要作者之一。 2022 年，《自然》杂志将 Huq 评为&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.nature.com/immersive/d41586-022-04185-3/index.html&quot;>;世界十大科学家之一&lt;/ a>;.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Huq 大力倡导年轻人在全球谈判中拥有发言权。 “我们这一代制造了混乱，他们这一代正在受苦。因此，他们必须有发言权。”他说。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;孟加拉国气候倡导者索哈努尔·拉赫曼 (Sohanur Ra​​hman) 形容他是“一位真正有远见的气候冠军，他无与伦比的遗产将成为未来数年和几代人的光辉榜样” 。他在对抗气候不公正方面的不懈努力将继续激励我们所有人。”&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com /environment/2022/nov/05/loss-and-damage-must-at-heart-of-cop27-talks-experts-say&quot;>;专家表示，损失和损害必须成为 Cop27 谈判的核心&lt;/a >;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;胡克以其坦率而闻名，他的讲话方式突破了气候术语和政治，提出了有关气候危机不平等的重大道德问题。在今年的 Cop28 之前，他写了一篇&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.icccad.net/opinion/cop28-must-set-up-a-new-dubai-loss-and-damage-fund&quot;>;​​公开文章致联合国气候峰会主席的信&lt;/a>;，主张建立新的损失和损害基金，同时概述如何实现这一目标的具体步骤。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“仅举我国孟加拉国的一个例子：每天都有超过 2000 名因气候原因而流离失所的人步行、骑自行车、乘船和公共汽车抵达达卡，然后消失在城市的贫民窟中，”他写道。 “没有人照顾他们，但他们是因人类引起的气候变化而被迫迁移的人，因此是《联合国气候变化框架公约》的责任。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这是一场胡克的朋友和同事将参与的战斗在他缺席&lt;a href=&quot;x-gu://list/mobile.guardianapis.com/international/lists/tag/environment/cop28&quot;>;下个月第 28 届缔约方大会&lt;/a>;及以后的会议期间，他在全球舞台上崭露头角。 “我非常感激他能活着看到损失和损害基金最终在 &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2022/nov/20/cop27-climate-summit-egypt -key-outcomes&quot;>;第 27 届缔约方大会在埃及举行，&lt;/a>;”Nakate 说道。 “我希望现在我们能够为他的遗产而奋斗，并确保其中充满真金白银。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;国际气候行动网络全球政治战略负责人 Harjeet Singh 在致辞中表示：“争取气候正义的斗争仍在继续。我保证，我将加倍努力，高举火炬，以更加饱满的热情和更加努力的精神去捍卫这一事业。我这样做是为了纪念您的遗产，感受您的指引和来自上天的祝福。”&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 01 Nov 2023 18:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Kamala Harris to call for urgent action on AI threat to democracy and privacy]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/nov/01/kamala-harris-to-call-for-urgent-action-on-ai-threat-to-democracy-and-privacy]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-11-01T09:46:33Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/a0f143d03aed0c62a92ddc9fdbbc91484c507b3e/0_138_4150_2490 /master/4150.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=c2a3e5bb997e1fad24705773a4d82ce7&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;卡马拉·哈里斯&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;人工智能对民主和隐私构成的短期威胁需要得到解决美国副总统卡马拉·哈里斯预计将在英国布莱奇利公园人工智能峰会之前发表演讲，阐述拜登政府的愿景，这一问题与长期存在的问题一样紧迫。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;在演讲中周三在伦敦参加会议之前，她将表示：“我们拒绝认为我们可以保护公众或推进创新的错误选择。我们可以而且必须两者兼而有之。随着这项技术的迅速发展，我们必须迅速采取行动。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;哈里斯希望超越有关人工智能未来可能构成的未来潜在（有时是推测性的、存在的威胁）的争论，去审视已经存在的危害。 &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;她会说，存在的威胁“毫无疑问是深刻的，需要全球采取行动。但让我们明确一点：还有其他威胁也需要我们采取行动，这些威胁目前正在造成伤害，而且对许多人来说，这些威胁也存在。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;哈里斯对对抗人工智能的技术特别感兴趣- 生成的语音呼叫可能试图从弱势群体那里窃取信息。她还希望采取措施追踪政府制作的真实数字内容以及人工智能生成或操纵的内容，包括通过数字签名、水印和其他标签技术。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;她将设置一系列测试人工智能的开发、测试和使用，包括：“代码中写入了谁的偏见？谁的利益得到满足？谁能获得快速采用的回报？谁受到的伤害最严重？如果出现问题，谁会受到伤害？谁参加了谈判？”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;她还将透露，30 个国家已同意签署美国发起的关于国家军队使用人工智能的政治宣言。绝大多数签署国都是西方国家，这表明一个新的冷战人工智能部门可能正在开始形成。她警告说，“人工智能网络攻击的规模超出了我们以前见过的规模，人工智能配制的生物武器可能危及数百万人的生命”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;政治宣言首先设定的目标2月份发布的草案中包括要求各国承诺“适用于整个军事领域的强有力且透明的规范，无论系统的功能或潜在影响的范围如何。”各国还将致力于继续讨论如何以负责任的方式开发、部署和使用军事人工智能能力，并继续与国际社会其他成员合作推动这些措施。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;她承诺，该宣言将保留自卫权以及各国在军事领域负责任地开发和使用人工智能的能力。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;她在英国的两天是她亲自向美国展示的机会她证实，美国商务部将建立美国人工智能安全研究所（US AISI），该研究所将制定“指导方针、用于评估和减轻危险能力以及进行评估以识别和减轻人工智能风险的工具、基准和最佳实践”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;该研究所将就诸如验证人类创建的内容、对人工智能生成的水印等问题制定技术指南内容，识别和减轻有害的算法歧视，确保透明度并支持采用保护隐私的人工智能。它还将成为未来劳动力安全可靠人工智能的驱动力。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com /news/audio/2023/nov/01/is-the-ai-safety-summit-already-too-late-podcast&quot;>;人工智能安全峰会是否已经太晚了？ – 播客&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;该机构将与国际同行机构共享信息并合作研究，其中包括英国计划中的人工智能安全研究所。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;美国政府内部拜登团队正在设立治理委员会来跟踪人工智能的进展，为机构领导层提供有关人工智能的建议，并协调和跟踪该机构的人工智能活动。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;哈里斯为国家监管的必要性辩护说：“历史已经在缺乏监管和强有力的政府监督的情况下，一些科技公司选择将利润置于客户的福祉、社区的安全和民主国家的稳定之上。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“解决问题的一个重要方法是除了我们已经完成的工作之外，这些挑战还需要通过立法来应对。在不扼杀创新的情况下加强人工智能安全的立法。”&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 01 Nov 2023 17:52:02 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Trump’s son Donald Jr to testify at real estate fraud trial in New York]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/nov/01/donald-trump-jr-testimony-fraud-trial-new-york]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-11-01T09:00:36Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/49d0069eb68ad3ca16deb458b895f9290b82556d/0_0_3500_2101 /master/3500.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=83a42ee2c2b1cd4eb0cd939a6e51162d&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;小唐纳德·特朗普&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;唐纳德·特朗普的长子今天将在&lt;a href =&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/oct/28/trump-fraud-trial-public-opinion&quot;>;围绕前总统商业帝国的纽约民事欺诈审判&lt;/a>;。&lt; /p>; &lt;p>;小唐纳德·特朗普（Donald Trump Jr）与他的父亲一起成为本案的被告，他将出庭作证，法官将考虑特朗普集团及其高管是否对其财产价值撒谎。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/oct/28/trump-fraud-Trial-public-opinion&quot;>;“审判”审判中”：特朗普的战略濒临崩溃&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;小唐和他的兄弟埃里克（公司执行副总裁）都将在法庭上接受质询星期。前总统唐纳德·特朗普预计将于下周作证，随后他的女儿伊万卡（不是本案被告）也将出庭。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In &lt;a href=&quot;https:/ /www.newsweek.com/donal-trump-jr-fraud-trial-death-penalty-1839573&quot;>;周一接受 Newsmax 采访&lt;/a>;时，小唐声称“主流媒体，[华盛顿]特区的人们……想把特朗普关进监狱一千年和/或死刑。真是恶心的东西，但这就是我们战斗的原因。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;法官阿瑟·恩戈伦 (Arthur Engoron) 已经裁定特朗普及其家族企业犯有欺诈行为。恩戈隆正在利用这次审判（重点关注余下的共谋、保险欺诈和伪造商业记录索赔）来决定惩罚措施。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;针对这位前总统、他的长子和其他特朗普高管的 2.5 亿美元欺诈案已经由纽约总检察长利蒂西亚·詹姆斯 (Letitia James) 办公室提起。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;该审判为法官审判，没有陪审团。恩戈隆（Engoron）正在主持此案，并将成为唯一的裁决者。由于这是民事审判，如果罪名成立，特朗普不会被送进监狱。虽然他不需要出庭，但他曾多次出庭，包括上周他的前调解人迈克尔·科恩的证词。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;恩戈隆在特朗普批评法官的法律助理后对他下达了禁言令。在社交媒体上。此后，他对这位前总统处以两次罚款：第一次是在违规帖子仍然在线后罚款 5,000 美元，然后是 &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/oct/25/trump-gag-order -judge-fraud-审判&quot;>;上周在法庭外发表评论，他被罚款 10,000 美元&lt;/a>;，他认为这构成了进一步的攻击。&lt;​​/p>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 01 Nov 2023 17:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Christchurch victims were left alone in mosque for 10 minutes amid chaos of attack, inquest hears]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/nov/01/christchurch-victims-were-left-alone-in-mosque-for-10-minutes-amid-chaos-of-attack-inquest-hears]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-11-01T07:03:52Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/761bdc324efc4abf8b57f94a95967eaa586292eb/0_18_1280_768 /master/1280.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=868fdf85f83bb1adef4380aedc805f33&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;新西兰基督城清真寺外的悼念活动。 &lt;/div>;&lt;p>;2019 年大规模枪击事件发生后，由于混乱和更多枪手的错误报告，导致基督城一座清真寺遭受白人至上主义恐怖袭击，受伤和垂死的受害者被单独留在建筑物中十分钟验尸调查得知，警察已离开现场并赶往其他地点。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;由于不确定是否即将发生更多袭击，医护人员没有进入新西兰两座清真寺中的第一座清真寺。遭到澳大利亚枪手袭击，直到袭击结束后 30 分钟。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;自大规模枪击事件发生以来，经核实的 2019 年 3 月 15 日大屠杀紧急响应时间表首次公开，当时闭路电视录像播放周三，对 51 名穆斯林信徒的死亡进行了死因调查。另有数十人在袭击中受伤。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/oct/24/ Police-response-scrutiny-inquest-christchurch-mosque-attack&quot;>;基督城清真寺袭击事件调查开始，详细审查警方的反应&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;布伦顿·塔兰特 (Brenton Tarrant)，28 岁，澳大利亚男子，他在网上变得激进，并于 2017 年移居新西兰，在那里他购买了枪支，并策划了这场充满仇恨的袭击，并于 2020 年因谋杀、谋杀未遂和恐怖主义被判处终身监禁，不得假释。 2020年的一个调查委员会得出的结论是，新西兰政府机构不可能提前阻止屠杀，“除非是偶然”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;但在验尸调查之前，没有其他调查仔细审查过新西兰当局在枪手发生后的反应。开枪了。尽管警方在袭击发生19分钟后将他抓获的行动受到广泛赞扬，但许多受访者表示，在一个相对和平的国家，严重的枪支犯罪很少见，这起袭击事件让他们遇到了他们从未预料到的场景。&lt;/自袭击发生以来，一些失去亲人的亲属一直有一个挥之不去的问题“围绕着为什么我们的亲人被留在清真寺一段时间而没有立即采取任何行动，而警察不允许我们或任何其他人去接他们代表许多死者家属的 3 月 15 日 Whānau 信托基金发言人拉希德·奥马尔 (Rashid Omar) 在调查开始前的一份书面声明中表示。他的儿子，&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/mar/15/four-years-after-christchurch-massacre-families-want-to-teach-world-about-love&quot; >;24 岁的塔里克·奥马尔 (Tariq Omar) 在努尔清真寺 (Masjid an-Nur) 被杀&lt;/a>;。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;周三在法庭上播放的清真寺闭路电视录像显示，武装罪犯小组的四名警察是第一批袭击发生后进入大楼，跑向车辆并离开，因为他们得知塔兰特向该市的第二座清真寺林伍德伊斯兰中心开枪。 &lt;br>;&lt;br>; 在他们被命令离开努尔清真寺（那里有 43 人死亡）之前，军官们已经开始对伤员进行分类。但他们很快就用完了绷带，并用无线电呼叫救护人员，情况越来越紧急。两人本周在基督城高等法院的调查中表示，他们不明白为什么没有人到达。&lt;br>;&lt;br>;其中一人被问及他认为离开清真寺后幸存的受害者会发生什么。 &lt;br>;&lt;br>;“我不确定，”他说。但他补充说，作为一名战术操作员，他的工作是逮捕枪手。&lt;br>;&lt;br>;第一批军官离开后，几乎十分钟过去了，其他人才进入清真寺。下午 2 点 15 分，也就是塔兰特在试图到达第三座清真寺时被撞进车里并被捕后一刻钟，两名护理人员在武装警察的护送下进入了里面。&lt;br>;&lt;br>; 那时，恐怖分子已经告诉逮捕他的警察称，他是当天策划袭击的 10 名枪手之一。这不是真的，但这一说法引起了努尔清真寺的更大恐慌。守卫清真寺大门的警官——他的名字和军衔，与许多提供证据的人一样，都被隐瞒了——告诉法庭，由于现场只剩下少数其他警官，他不想让清真寺毫无防备地进去帮助人们。 .&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;警方通讯渠道上的另一份错误报告——有关基督城医院枪击事件的报道——转移了那里的其他警察的注意力。当地区指挥中心的一名高级官员通过警方无线电发出惊慌失措的警告称，已经被捕的塔兰特即将返回现场时，医疗救助的到来进一步陷入困境。&lt;br>;&lt;br>; 警探达里尔·斯威尼 (Darryl Sweeney)他不知道自己正在观看塔兰特袭击事件视频的延迟版本，枪手在互联网上现场直播了该视频。他继续讲述恐怖分子返回清真寺的过程三分钟，站在大楼外的警察困惑地听着，他们知道报告不实。一名官员告诉法庭，他无法闯入通讯频道来平息警报。&lt;br>;&lt;br>;包括斯威尼在内的许多警官表示，根据当时掌握的信息，他们不会采取任何不同的行动。 &lt;br>;&lt;br>; 验尸官布丽吉特·温德利 (Brigitte Windley) 将在基督城高等法院举行为期七周的听证会后决定是否有任何遇难者能够获救。预计她将在 2024 年公布调查前 13 个问题中的 10 个问题的调查结果。&lt;br>;&lt;br>;但 10 月 24 日开始的调查已经回答了一些长期存在的问题。 &lt;a href=&quot;https://coronialservices.justice.govt.nz/assets/d836SD43-Evidential-Overview-for-Christchurch-Masjid-attacks.pdf&quot;>;警方于 2021 年 2 月发布的证据报告&lt;/a>;说第一辆救护车于下午 2 点 08 分“获准进入”清真寺。 – 但周三在法庭上播放的闭路电视录像显示，他们七分钟后进入了大楼。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;同一份报告称，所有遇难者都遭受了“不可避免的致命伤害，这意味着如果他们受到伤害，他们将无法幸存”更快地撤离[……]。” &lt;br>;&lt;br>; 调查尚未听取病理学家、医生或救护人员的医学证据。基督城的救护车服务机构 St John 是一家慈善机构，一些护理人员是志愿者。&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 01 Nov 2023 15:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Russia-Ukraine war live: world expects success ‘too quickly’, says Zelenskiy; US senators indicate Ukraine funding support]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2023/nov/01/russia-ukraine-war-live-world-expects-success-too-quickly-says-zelenskiy-us-senators-indicate-ukraine-funding-support]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-11-01T07:14:48Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/2422aee2d0602868f1ead818a6da9c32704b94d6/0_0_7500_5000 /master/7500.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=5eba5a772671311f8c4f54702aa99b0d&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;乌克兰士兵于 10 月 31 日在 Bakhmut 方向用改装为多发射系统的车辆发射 grad 炮弹2023&lt;/div>;&lt;br>;&lt;hr>;&lt;div>;获取更多RSS：&lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.net&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https: //feedx.net&lt;/a>; &lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.best&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.best&lt;/a>;&lt; br>;&lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 01 Nov 2023 15:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Hungary anti-LGBT law sees under-18s barred from World Press Photo exhibition]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/nov/01/hungary-anti-lgbt-law-under-18s-barred-world-press-photo-exhibition]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-11-01T06:09:24Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/f61989877d0e62f6ef89d31a4850daf98bd5ed06/0_331_4961_2977 /master/4961.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=e35c0684139f69ab4d92a9f805fcfb24&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;世界新闻摄影展的照片之一，该展览在匈牙利已不对 18 岁以下青少年开放。 &lt;/div>;&lt;p>;匈牙利右翼民粹主义政府认定其部分照片违反了限制 LGBTQ+ 内容的有争议的法律，因此禁止 18 岁以下的人参观今年在布达佩斯举行的世界新闻摄影展。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这一享有盛誉的展览在布达佩斯的匈牙利国家博物馆展出，每年接待来自世界各地的超过四百万参观者。其使命是展示杰出的新闻摄影，为全球观众提供一系列重要事件的视觉报道。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;菲律宾摄影记者汉娜·雷耶斯·莫拉莱斯 (Hannah Reyes Morales) 拍摄的一组五张照片促使一位极右翼匈牙利议员提交了文件向文化部提出投诉，文化部发现他们违反了匈牙利禁止向未成年人展示 LGBTQ+ 内容的法律。现在，即使得到父母的同意，18岁以下的人也不再被允许参观展览。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian .com/world/2022/jun/30/luxembourg-same-sex-husband-seated-viktor-orban-nato-summit&quot;>;卢森堡首相的同性丈夫在峰会上坐在维克托·欧尔班旁边&lt;/a>;&lt;/p >; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;这些照片记录了菲律宾一个由 LGBTQ+ 老人组成的社区，他们几十年来一直住在一个家中，随着年龄的增长互相照顾，一些社区成员穿着变装、化着妆。 &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;世界新闻摄影执行董事 Joumana El Zein Khoury 表示，“如此积极、如此包容”的照片系列遭到匈牙利政府的攻击，这令人担忧。她说，这是第一次其中一个展览在欧洲面临审查。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“事实上，特定类型的观众的参观受到限制，这确实让我们感到非常震惊，”Khoury说。 “令人难以置信的是，这个特定的图像、这个特定的故事，而且令人难以置信的是它发生在欧洲。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Tamas Revesz，前世界新闻摄影评审团成员，一直是该活动的组织者。匈牙利举办了三十多年的展览，他表示，展览中的许多照片——例如对乌克兰战争的报道——比莫拉莱斯的系列“严肃和令人震惊一千倍”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;考虑到这一点他说，每年在匈牙利参观展览的大约 5 万人中，有一半是学生，成千上万的匈牙利年轻人将无法观看该藏品，即使是那些不包含 LGBTQ+ 内容的图像。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>; &lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2022/may/23/the-guardian-view-on-viktor-orbans-brussels-bashing-a- rekoning-must-come&quot;>;《卫报》对维克多·欧尔班的布鲁塞尔抨击的看法：清算必须到来 |社论&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;禁止年轻人参观展览的举措是匈牙利政府（由民族主义总理维克托·欧尔班领导）的最新举措，旨在限制宣传材料的供应。或在媒体（包括电视、电影、广告和文学）中向未成年人描述同性恋。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;虽然政府坚称 2021 年《儿童保护》法旨在使儿童免受所谓的性宣传，但它此举引发了欧盟 15 个国家的法律诉讼，欧盟委员会主席乌苏拉·冯德莱恩 (Ursula von der Leyen) 称其为“耻辱”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;摄影师雷耶斯·莫拉莱斯 (Reyes Morales) 在一份电子邮件声明中表示，这些拍摄对象她的照片是菲律宾 LGBTQ+ 人群的“偶像和榜样”，并且它们“不危险或有害”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;匈牙利文化部没有回应采访请求。&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 01 Nov 2023 14:22:02 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Seoul to trial seatless subway carriages to cut rush-hour congestion]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/nov/01/seoul-to-trial-seatless-subway-carriages-to-cut-rush-hour-congestion]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-11-01T06:16:14Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/4358346f13db032a18b8d19d0178734af7eb0790/0_0_6001_4000 /master/6001.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=39b8bb4c419966513d1f5a237a3a0914&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;首尔地铁乘客&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;首尔地铁系统计划引入无座位车厢列车其运营商宣布，为了缓解高峰时段的拥堵。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;该试点计划将于 1 月开始，将涉及在韩国首都两座城市运行的地铁列车上拆除两节车厢的座位。首尔地铁周三表示，早晚高峰时段有 9 条主要线路。它是一个更广泛项目的一部分，旨在减少世界上最繁忙的地铁系统之一的拥堵&lt;/a>;.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;据首尔地铁称，到 2023 年第三季度，正在进行试验的 4 号线和 7 号线内部的拥堵程度分别达到了运力的 193.4% 和 164.2% ，在最繁忙的时间。随着座位的拆除，预计每节地铁车厢的高峰拥堵程度将降至 4 号线的 153.4% 和 7 号线的 130.1%。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span >;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/13/seoul-south-korea-secret-tunnel-mystery-3000-square-metre&quot;>;首尔的秘密空间：广阔的神秘隧道首次揭晓&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;首尔地铁&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.seoulmetro.co.kr/en/page.do?menuIdx=649&quot;>; &lt;/a>; 管理着世界上最大的城市铁路网络之一，包括 9 条线路和 275 个车站，每天为大约 700 万名通勤者提供服务。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“如果试点项目证明有效，我们将在首尔地铁首席执行官白浩 (Baek Ho) 表示：“未来，确保市民能够更舒适、安全地使用地铁。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;除此消息外，首尔地铁还增加了高峰时段两条拥堵线路上的地铁列车班次。一些当地媒体询问该举措是否最终会结束令人恐惧的“jiokcheol”，这是一个结合了“地狱”和“地铁”的术语它捕捉到了乘客在过度拥挤的地铁列车上每天所经历的挫败感。&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 01 Nov 2023 14:22:02 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Air pollution raises risk of type 2 diabetes, says landmark Indian study]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2023/nov/01/air-pollution-raises-risk-of-type-2-diabetes-says-landmark-indian-study-acc]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-11-01T06:00:32Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/e67bbc7462d8809f991c77b945ff9135e50a8b0d/0_0_3826_2551 /master/3826.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=fce72fe66d78bd24bd580f827c873e74&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;新德里的雾霾中，人们走在通往印度门的路上。印度是世界上空气污染最严重的国家之一。&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;印度第一项此类研究发现，吸入受污染的空气会增加患 2 型糖尿病的风险。在德里和南部城市金奈进行的研究发现，吸入含有大量 PM2.5 颗粒的空气会导致高血糖并增加 2 型糖尿病发病率。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;吸入时，PM2.5 颗粒 –它们比一根头发丝细 30 倍，可以进入血液并导致多种呼吸系统和心血管疾病。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://drc.bmj.com/content/bmjdrc/ 11/5/e003333.full.pdf&quot;>;这项研究&lt;/a>;是 2010 年开始的印度慢性病研究的一部分。它是第一个关注环境 PM2.5 暴露与 2 型疾病之间联系的研究印度是&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.iqair.com/gb/world-most-polluted-countries&quot;>;世界上空气污染最严重的国家&lt;/a>;之一。&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-atom-id=&quot;1b91c1e2-549d-4295-a674-9d77a46cf5d2&quot; data-atom-type=&quot;guide&quot;>; &lt;详细信息 data-snippet-id=&quot;1b91c1e2-549d-4295-a674-9d77a46cf5d2&quot; data- snippet-type=&quot;guide&quot;>; &lt;summary>; &lt;span>;快速指南&lt;/span>; &lt;h4>;常见情况&lt;/h4>;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot;>; &lt;span>; &lt;svg width=&quot;18px&quot; height=&quot;18px&quot; viewBox=&quot;0 0 18 18&quot;>; &lt;路径 d=&quot;M8.2 0h1.6l.4 7.8 7.8.4v1.6l-7.8.4-.4 7.8H8.2l-.4-7.8L0 9.8V8.2l7.8-.4.4-7.8z&quot; />; &lt;/svg>; 显示&lt;/span>; &lt;span>; &lt;svg width=&quot;32px&quot; height=&quot;32px&quot; viewBox=&quot;0 0 32 32&quot;>; &lt;rect x=&quot;5&quot; y=&quot;15&quot; width=&quot;22&quot; height=&quot;3&quot;>;&lt;/rect>; &lt;/svg>; 隐藏&lt;/span>; &lt;/span>; &lt;/summary>; &lt;div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p >; 非传染性疾病 (NCD) 造成的死亡人数巨大，而且还在不断上升。每年有 5,600 万人死于这些疾病，其中约 4,100 万人死于这些疾病，其中四分之三生活在发展中国家。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;非传染性疾病就是这样；非传染性疾病就是这样；与病毒不同，你无法感染它们。相反，它们是由遗传、生理、环境和行为因素共同引起的。 The main types are cancers, chronic respiratory illnesses, diabetes and cardiovascular disease – heart attacks and stroke. Approximately 80% are preventable, and all are on the rise, spreading inexorably around the world as ageing populations and lifestyles pushed by economic growth and urbanisation make being unhealthy a global phenomenon.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;NCDs, once seen as illnesses of the wealthy, now have a grip on the poor. Disease, disability and death are perfectly designed to create and widen inequality – and being poor makes it less likely you will be diagnosed accurately or treated.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Investment in tackling these common and chronic conditions that kill 71% of us is incredibly low, while the cost to families, economies and communities is staggeringly high.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In low-income countries NCDs – typically slow and debilitating illnesses – are seeing a fraction of the money needed being invested or donated. Attention remains focused on the threats from communicable diseases, yet cancer death rates have long sped past the death toll from malaria, TB and HIV/Aids combined.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&#39;A common condition&#39; is a Guardian series reporting on NCDs in the developing world: their prevalence, the solutions, the causes and consequences, telling the stories of people living with these illnesses.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;b>;Tracy McVeigh, editor&lt;/b>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;/div>; &lt;footer>; &lt;div>; &lt;div>; Was this helpful? &lt;/div>;&lt;button value=&quot;like&quot; aria-label=&quot;Yes&quot;>; &lt;svg width=&quot;40px&quot; height=&quot;40px&quot; viewBox=&quot;0 0 40 40&quot;>; &lt;path fill=&quot;#FFF&quot; d=&quot;M33.78 22.437l-4.228 13.98L27.93 37.5 5.062 34.14V15.503l7.8-1.517L24.354 2.5h1.624L28.9 5.426l-4.548 8.67h.107l10.477 1.31&quot; />; &lt;/svg>;&lt;/button>; &lt;button value=&quot;dislike&quot; aria-label=&quot;No&quot;>; &lt;svg width=&quot;40px&quot; height=&quot;40px&quot; viewBox=&quot;0 0 40 40&quot;>; &lt;path fill=&quot;#FFF&quot; d=&quot;M33.78 22.437l-4.228 13.98L27.93 37.5 5.062 34.14V15.503l7.8-1.517L24.354 2.5h1.624L28.9 5.426l-4.548 8.67h.107l10.477 1.31&quot; />; &lt;/svg>;&lt;/button>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div hidden aria-role=&quot;alert&quot; aria-live=&quot;polite&quot;>; Thank you for your feedback. &lt;/div>; &lt;/footer>; &lt;/details>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;The average annual PM2.5 levels in Delhi was 82-100μg/m&lt;sup>;3&lt;/sup>; and in Chennai was 30-40μg/m&lt;sup>;3&lt;/sup>;, according to the study,&lt;strong>; &lt;/strong>;many times the &lt;a href=&quot;https://iris.who.int/bitstream/handle/10665/345329/9789240034228-eng.pdf&quot;>;WHO limits of 5μg/m&lt;sup>;3&lt;/sup>;&lt;/a>;. &lt;a href=&quot;https://cpcb.nic.in/uploads/National_Ambient_Air_Quality_Standards.pdf&quot;>;India&#39;s national air quality standards&lt;/a>; are 40μg/m&lt;sup>;3&lt;/sup>;.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;There is also a &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lansea/article/PIIS2772-3682(23)00016-1/fulltext&quot;>;high burden&lt;/a>; of non-communicable diseases, including diabetes, hypertension and heart disease in India; 11.4% of the population – 101 million people – are living with diabetes, and about 136 million are pre-diabetic, according to a &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.thelancet.com/journals/landia/article/PIIS2213-8587(23)00119-5/fulltext&quot;>;paper &lt;/a>;published in the Lancet in June. The average diabetes prevalence in the &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.oecd-ilibrary.org/sites/83231356-en/index.html?itemId=/content/component/83231356-en&quot;>;European Union&lt;/a>; was 6.2% in 2019, and 8.6% in the &lt;a href=&quot;https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/5a82c07340f0b6230269c82d/Diabetesprevalencemodelbriefing.pdf&quot;>;UK &lt;/a>;in 2016.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The Lancet study found India&#39;s diabetes prevalence to be higher than previous estimations and showed a higher number of diabetics in urban than rural India.&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;4fa587f64293c11264aa593e43fac6af547ed5a0&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/4fa587f64293c11264aa593e43fac6af547ed5a0/0_0_3328_1956/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;An Indian commuter wears a mask to protect himself against dust and pollution as he waits to cross a road in Chennai.&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;588&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;An Indian commuter wears a mask to protect himself against dust and pollution as he waits to cross a road in Chennai.&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;Photograph: Arun Sankar/AFP/Getty Images&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;In the BMJ study, the researchers followed a cohort of 12,000 men and women in Delhi and Chennai from 2010 to 2017 and measured their blood sugar levels periodically. Using satellite data and air pollution exposure models, they determined the air pollution in the locality of each participant in that timeframe.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;They found that one month of exposure to PM2.5 led to elevated levels of blood sugar and prolonged exposure of one year or more led to increased risk of diabetes. They found for every 10μg/m&lt;sup>;3&lt;/sup>; increase in annual average PM2.5 level in the two cities, the risk for diabetes increased by 22%.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2023/sep/29/diabetes-undiagnosed-40-per-cent-of-cases-worldwide-survey-acc&quot;>;Global survey finds diabetes goes undiagnosed in 40% of cases&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;“Given the pathophysiology of Indians – low BMI with a high proportion of fat – we are more prone to diabetes than the western population,” said Siddhartha Mandal, lead investigator of the study and a researcher at Centre for Chronic Disease Control, Delhi.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The addition of air pollution – an environmental factor – with lifestyle changes in the past 20 to 30 years is fuelling the increasing burden of diabetes, he said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“Until now, we had assumed that diet, obesity and physical exercise were some of the factors explaining why urban Indians had higher prevalence of diabetes than rural Indians,” said Dr V Mohan, chairman of the Madras Diabetes Research Foundation and one of the authors of the paper. “This study is an eye-opener because now we have found a new cause for diabetes that is pollution.”&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;5ecd4f8cfe7b7b529af8452c2d6833e170f63d88&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/5ecd4f8cfe7b7b529af8452c2d6833e170f63d88/0_0_4024_2754/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;A man has his blood sugar checked at a mobile clinic outside the Geeta Colony area of Delhi. Cases of diabetes and hypertension have been rising rapidly among slum dwellers in India.&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;684&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;A man has his blood sugar checked at a mobile clinic outside the Geeta Colony area of Delhi.&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;Photograph: Prakash Singh/AFP/Getty Images&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;Another &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/10.1161/HYPERTENSIONAHA.120.15373?url_ver=Z39.88-2003&amp;amp;rfr_id=ori:rid:crossref.org&amp;amp;rfr_dat=cr_pub%20%200pubmed#d12546699e1&quot;>;study&lt;/a>; on the same cohort in Delhi, found average annual exposure to PM2.5 in Delhi (92μg/m&lt;sup>;3&lt;/sup>;) led to increase in blood pressure levels and higher likelihood of developing hypertension.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Together, the studies show that the higher than safe levels of PM2.5 in the air in Indian cities cause diabetes and hypertension that could lead to atherosclerosis (the build up of fatty deposits in the arteries), heart attacks and heart failures, said Mandal.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;PM2.5 contains sulfates, nitrates, heavy metals and black carbon that can damage the lining of blood vessels and increase blood pressure by stiffening the arteries. The particles can get deposited in the fat cells and cause inflammation and can also attack the heart muscle directly, said Dr Dorairaj Prabhakaran, cardiologist and executive director of the Centre for Chronic Disease Control and one of the authors of the paper.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Acting as an endocrine disruptor, PM2.5 hampers insulin production in the body as well as its effect.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In urban India there has been a rise of hypothyroidism, polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS) and gestational diabetes. This study shows that pollution may play a part in causing all of these as it disrupts the endocrine system that produces all hormones in the body, said Mohan.&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;075ae780893192d21fe4234fc92b4568f1d78216&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/075ae780893192d21fe4234fc92b4568f1d78216/0_0_3500_2416/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Indian commuters drive amid heavy smog in Delhi on 7 November 2017. The city woke up to a choking blanket of smog that day, as air quality in the world&#39;s most polluted capital city reached hazardous levels.&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;690&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;Indian commuters drive amid heavy smog in Delhi.&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;Photograph: Prakash Singh/AFP/Getty Images&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;The researchers are now working to understand the impact of pollution on cholesterol and vitamin D levels in the body, and its impact on the life cycle of individuals, including birth weight, pregnant women&#39;s health, insulin resistance in adolescents, and the risk for Parkinson&#39;s and Alzheimer&#39;s disease, among others.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;While its findings are alarming, the study gives scientists hope that bringing down pollution can decrease the burden of diabetes, as well as other non-communicable diseases, said Prabhakaran.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Some public policy initiatives have shown results. Since a public outcry about air pollution in 2016, the central and Delhi government have banned older diesel vehicles, limited construction, built highways that bypass the city, and banned the burning of crops. Reports suggest there was a 22% reduction in PM2.5 levels between 2016 and 2021.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“This is a modest but welcome reduction. Similar measures adapted to local conditions are urgently needed across the country,” said Prabhakaran.&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 01 Nov 2023 14:22:02 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Love bikes, hate ‘wild parking’ – Dutch city puts rule-breakers on the rack]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/nov/01/love-bikes-hate-wild-parking-dutch-city-puts-rule-breakers-on-the-rack]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-11-01T05:00:31Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/58a68b4ca552a79773a24a7ad02294ccad5bddee/0_374_4100_2460/master/4100.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=507e3a77a1c15fc5e5e05ac512ac6775&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;People on bikes wait at a traffic light&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;Officials in the Netherlands, a country with &lt;a href=&quot;https://nos.nl/l/2313742&quot;>;more bicycles than people&lt;/a>;, are tackling a plague of “wild parking” by confiscating illegally stationed bikes and increasing the penalties to get them back.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;This year the southern city of Maastricht – &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/good-university-guide-2020-maastricht-university-international-students-holland-debt-m6h2rl35j&quot;>;beloved of international students&lt;/a>; – banned people from “orphaning” their bikes by deserting them on the street. Now it is doubling the fines it charges people who want to reclaim impounded bicycles.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;To be legal, cyclists in the inner city must park at a bike rack – securing it to railings or a lamp-post is a no-no.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;From January, those who have had a bicycle confiscated will need to pay €50 (£43) to release it from the pound rather than €25.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Maastricht has just over &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.cbs.nl/nl-nl/visualisaties/dashboard-bevolking/regionaal/inwoners&quot;>;120,000 inhabitants&lt;/a>;, around &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.maastrichtuniversity.nl/nl/over-de-um/organisatie/feiten-cijfers&quot;>;a fifth of them students&lt;/a>;, and bike parking has been an issue for years.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;This year, &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.gemeentemaastricht.nl/stad/actueel/nieuws/1-januari-bedrag-voor-terugkrijgen-fout-geparkeerde-fiets-50-euro#:~:text=We%20willen%20goed%20en%20veilig,25%20euro%20naar%2050%20euro.&quot;>;2,159 “illegally parked” bikes have so far been cut away&lt;/a>;, according to the council. Last year the total was 2,611. A new&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.maastrichtbereikbaar.nl/hoe-reis-ik/ik-fiets/maastricht-posifiets&quot;>; campaign aims to encourage responsible cycling&lt;/a>;.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“It is positive to see that ever more people are using a bike,” said the mayor of Maastricht, Wim Hillenaar.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“But on the other hand, this sometimes brings problems in public space … and this decision is because the number of incorrectly parked bicycles remains too high despite all efforts.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In the city, there are council bike storage facilities where bikes can be kept for a maximum of 14 days and it is forbidden to park anywhere except at a bike rack in the inner city.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Like &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/jan/18/underwater-bike-garage-solves-amsterdam-stations-storage-headache&quot;>;Amsterdam&lt;/a>; and &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/cities/2019/aug/19/dutch-take-cycling-to-a-new-level-with-worlds-biggest-bike-park&quot;>;Utrecht&lt;/a>;, Maastricht has been building bike garages but has found people &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.parool.nl/amsterdam/stalling-bij-cs-nauwelijks-gebruikt-moeten-wachten-maakt-mensen-razend~b763028b/&quot;>;still tend to secure their bikes to lamp-posts&lt;/a>; since parking in &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.fietsersbond.nl/onderweg/fietsdiefstal/feiten-en-cijfers-over-fietsdiefstal/&quot;>;racks or garages does not necessarily deter thieves&lt;/a>;.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;But Mark Mülders, the head of the GreenLeft local party, is concerned that the penalties could be counterproductive.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“This is indeed a hot topic,” he said. “GreenLeft wants a city where there is as little car traffic as possible … and in all honesty, I&#39;m happy if people take the bike instead of the car.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“I would rather that they get a fine for incorrectly parking their car than their bike because everyone who cycles has made a contribution to a car-free inner city.”&lt;/p>;&lt;br>;&lt;hr>;&lt;div>;获取更多RSS：&lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.net&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.net&lt;/a>; &lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.best&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.best&lt;/a>;&lt;br>;&lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 01 Nov 2023 13:52:02 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Cigarette-style climate warnings on food could cut meat consumption, study suggests]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/nov/01/cigarette-style-climate-warnings-on-food-could-cut-meat-consumption-study-suggests]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-11-01T05:00:32Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/8f0a40854edb48172d71202b27e389aa502b3969/297_430_2737_1642/master/2737.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=7904b00fdb9153120e963be69f3c56ca&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;A hamburger with a warning on a toothpick which says: &#39;Warning: Eating meat contributes to climate change.&#39;&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;People are used to seeing stark warnings on tobacco products alerting them about the potentially deadly risks to health. Now a study suggests similar labelling on food could help them make wiser choices about not just their health, but the health of the planet.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The research, by academics at Durham University, found that warning labels including a graphic image – similar to those warning of impotence, heart disease or lung cancer on cigarette packets – could reduce selections of meals containing meat by 7-10%.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;It is a change that could have a material impact on the future of the planet. According to a recent YouGov poll, 72% of the UK population classify themselves as meat-eaters. But the Climate Change Committee (CCC), which advises the government on its net zero goals, has said the UK needs to slash its meat consumption by 20% by 2030, and 50% by 2050, in order to meet them.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Jack Hughes, a PhD candidate who led the Durham study, said: “When you combine that [CCC advice] with the fact that high meat intake is linked to lots of health issues, and the way that we currently farm, or certainly some of the most common ways of farming, are also very heavily linked to the potential of pandemic outbreaks, it becomes clear that there are multiple reasons why the current way that we eat meat is maybe not the best way to do it.”&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/oct/27/revealed-industry-figures-declaration-scientists-backing-meat-eating&quot;>;Revealed: the industry figures behind &#39;declaration of scientists&#39; backing meat eating&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;Hughes and colleagues split 1,001 meat-eating adults into four groups, and showed each group pictures of hot meat, fish, vegetarian and vegan canteen-style meals – ranging from burgers to quiche – with either a health warning label, a climate warning label, a pandemic warning label, or no label at all.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Pandemic warnings proved the most effective at dissuading participants from eating the meat options, reducing choices of them by 10%, followed by health warnings at 8.8%, then climate warnings at 7.4% – but researchers said the differences were not statistically significant, and that participants had judged the climate warnings to be the most credible.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Researchers believe their findings could help encourage changes in gastronomic choices that could ultimately benefit the environment. “Reaching net zero is a priority for the nation and the planet,” Hughes said. “As warning labels have already been shown to reduce smoking as well as drinking of sugary drinks and alcohol, using a warning label on meat-containing products could help us achieve this if introduced as national policy.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The study is published in the journal Appetite.&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 01 Nov 2023 13:52:02 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Baltic Sea faces ‘critical challenges’ on climate and biodiversity, report warns]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/nov/01/baltic-sea-faces-critical-challenges-climate-biodiversity-report]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-11-01T05:00:32Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/a046b9be29c8658534090aa98774c27b04410284/0_230_6192_3715/master/6192.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=9752dc82db436093672eaac593272624&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;People clean up oil from among the rocks on the shore&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;The Baltic Sea faces “critical challenges” due to the climate crisis and degradation of biodiversity, a report has said, as Sweden&#39;s coastguard battled to contain the impact of an oil spill off the country&#39;s southern shore.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In the most comprehensive audit of its kind to date, experts at the Baltic Marine Environment Protection Commission (Helcom) said on Tuesday there had been “little to no improvement” in the health of the body of water between 2016 and 2021.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Fish stocks were at dangerously low levels, while pollution, land use and resource extraction continued to put pressure on the sea, the report said.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/oct/31/swedish-authorities-battle-to-stabilise-stricken-ferry-leaking-oil-into-baltic-sea&quot;>;Swedish authorities battle to stabilise stricken ferry leaking oil into Baltic Sea&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;On Monday the Swedish coastguard extracted about 20 cubic metres of oil from the Baltic, bringing the total to about 50 cubic metres, after &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/oct/31/swedish-authorities-battle-to-stabilise-stricken-ferry-leaking-oil-into-baltic-sea&quot;>;a ferry ran aground three times&lt;/a>; off Hörvik in southern Sweden.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The coastguard said on Tuesday it hoped the Marco Polo would be salvaged on Wednesday and taken to a port in Karlshamn to prevent a risk of further oil spills.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Surrounded by nine countries including Sweden, Finland, Denmark and Russia, the Baltic&#39;s relatively shallow, low-saline, brackish enclosed water makes it a unique marine environment. These properties also mean it is especially vulnerable to pollution and changing environmental conditions.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The State of the Baltic Sea 2023 report found that despite efforts to improve its environment, overall conditions had not improved while some indicators had worsened.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Jannica Haldin, the deputy executive secretary of Helcom and coordinator of the report, said: “The findings serve as a sobering reminder that the Baltic Sea faces critical challenges stemming from human activities. The importance of transboundary cooperation, a shift towards genuinely environmentally sustainable practices and long-term commitment cannot be overstated.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Human activities including pollution, overfishing and habitat destruction had affected the ecosystem, leading to an overall decline in biodiversity, the report found.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Eutrophication – a largely human-made phenomenon in which excess nutrients such as nitrogen and phosphorus cause algae blooms – was also a problem, it said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The Baltic&#39;s poor environmental status was also affecting the profitability of fisheries and tourism, the report found.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;There were some bright spots. Reductions in nutrient inputs and hazardous substances, as well as work on biodiversity and conservation, were found to have shown signs of success in some parts of the Baltic and several former pollution hotspots were removed from the latest assessment. The share of marine protected areas in the region was found to be increasing.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;But the climate crisis was increasingly taking its toll, the report said, resulting in reduced ice cover, more extreme weather and rising water temperatures.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;A Baltic Sea action plan, devised by Helcom in 2021, calls for strengthened biodiversity, a reduction in environmental pressures and an improvement in the overall health of the Baltic&#39;s ecosystem.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“Still, the current assessment results suggest that the recovery rate for biodiversity today is too slow,” Haldin said. “The deteriorated status presented in this report is directly linked to the activities and priorities of us as a society.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;She added: “Ensuring that the Baltic Sea ecosystem maintains and improves its function is entirely dependent on how well we can manage our activities to ensure that they are truly sustainable and enhance the resilience of the ecosystem, both in the near future and long term.”&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 01 Nov 2023 13:52:02 +0800</pubDate></item></channel></rss>